      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Materialists’",
      "note": "Celine Song's Past Lives follow-up",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Materialists",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Dakota Johnson plays a New York matchmaker torn between an ex (Chris Evans) and a wealthy new bachelor (Pedro Pascal). Both hosts admire Song's writing and craft, from the needle drops to the wealth-and-class staging, but split on the leads: Sean can't buy Johnson carrying the emotion, Amanda finds Pascal miscast. The height-surgery reveal lands; the upstate ending gets loose."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "list",
      "heading": "The Top Five Movie Love Triangles",
      "note": "Sean and Amanda's separate ballots, one shared No. 1",
      "picks": [
        {
          "title": "Broadcast News",
          "year": 1987,
          "by": "Both",
          "note": "No. 1: the one where she picks no one, which is the whole point."
        },
        {
          "title": "Casablanca",
          "year": 1942,
          "by": "Sean",
          "note": "No. 2: an incomplete list without it; did she pick right?"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Philadelphia Story",
          "year": 1940,
          "by": "Amanda",
          "note": "No. 2: the blueprint every other triangle is built from."
        },
        {
          "title": "Being John Malkovich",
          "year": 1999,
          "by": "Sean",
          "note": "No. 3: two women and one man, via a portal into his head."
        },
        {
          "title": "Reality Bites",
          "year": 1994,
          "by": "Amanda",
          "note": "No. 3: Hawke vs. Stiller, and which one you pick tracks your age."
        },
        {
          "title": "Burning",
          "year": 2018,
          "by": "Sean",
          "note": "No. 4: Lee Chang-dong on losing to a rival who just has moves you don't."
        },
        {
          "title": "Something's Gotta Give",
          "year": 2003,
          "by": "Amanda",
          "note": "No. 4: a 'maybe she should've chosen the other guy' movie, thanks to Keanu."
        },
        {
          "title": "Fight Club",
          "year": 1999,
          "by": "Sean",
          "note": "No. 5: commit to the girl, or become an agent of anarchy."
        },
        {
          "title": "Past Lives",
          "year": 2023,
          "by": "Amanda",
          "note": "No. 5: Celine Song working this same terrain the first time."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘The Life of Chuck’",
      "note": "Mike Flanagan's Stephen King adaptation",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Life of Chuck",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "A non-horror King novella structured backward across three acts (an apocalypse, a street dance, a childhood) that won the TIFF Audience Award. Sean, a Flanagan and King believer, lets it have him; Amanda is charmed despite herself but fights the audiobook-length Nick Offerman narration. Tom Hiddleston, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Mark Hamill, Mia Sara."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Mike Flanagan on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Life of Chuck",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Flanagan on adapting the least cynical thing King's written, keeping the structure intact, and walking the line between corniness and sincerity with no minor key in the score."
        },
